<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by PCS (Public and Commercial Services Union) (JRR 0016)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS, the Public and Commercial Services union, is the largest trade union in the civil service and represents </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">over 14,000 members working in the Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> (MoJ)</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">. As the union representing the majority of members working in HM Courts and Tribunals (HMCTS) we are ideally placed to judge what improvements should be made to improve access to justice.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS be</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">lieves that </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">judicial reviews </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">are of constitutional importance</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> as a useful tool in holding the government of the day to account, protecting the public interest, and in improving policy-making. T</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">he proposals in the Ministry of Justice’s latest consultation d</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">ocument, taken together with those in the Transforming Legal Aid and previous </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">judicial review </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">consultations, represent a significant attack on the ability of individuals, charities, </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">non-g</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">overnmental </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">organisations </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">and trade unions to have access to challeng</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">e decisions made by the state. We are concerned that they will serve to make the government and public bodies less accountable as decision makers. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">In its consultation paper, t</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">he Government points to the rise in the number of applications as a major facto</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">r in the need to review the system. Administrative Court data is highlighted that shows there were only 4,500 applications for judicial review in 1998, as opposed to 12,400 in 2012. However, there is no evidence that addresses whether the underlying proble</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">m is the result of faults in the initial decisions that are being challenged rather than the processes that are already in place.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">We believe that there needs to be proper analysis as to the reasons for delay in the hearing of judicial review</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">. There is an</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> issue with a lack of resources in our courts system that urgently needs to be addressed rather than seeking to cut down on democratic accountability.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS is concerned that too many of the decisions being made that restrict access to justice, are predicat</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">ed on budget cuts and, in this case, to make the government less accountable. We believe that more funding could be raised for the justice system if the monies collected through fine enforcement were reinvested directly into MoJ.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Standing</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and third party interventions</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS is particularly concerned about the proposed changes relating to standing. The Government claims too wide an approach is taken to who may bring a claim, allowing judicial reviews to be brought by individuals or groups wit</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">hout a direct and tangible </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">interest in the subject matter to which the claim relates, sometimes for reasons only of publicity or to cause delay. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> proposals are </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">in fact </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">simply seeking to limit what the Government concedes are re</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">latively successful (paragraph 78) cases. The proposals will limit the potential for organisations such as trade unions who may seek to apply for a judicial review on behalf of the members it represents.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS has </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">no problem with the current “sufficient int</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">erest” test for standing. </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">We have not seen any evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">to the government’s assertion that</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> this is a problem sufficient enough to warrant these proposed changes. If NGOs, charities, faith groups, trade unions and campaigning groups were unable to bring jud</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">icial reviews, some government action will be impossible to challenge as there are times when an individual is not able to bring a challenge</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> themselves</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">The government could only find 50 cases between 2007 and 2011 lodged by “NGOs, charities, pressure </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">groups and faith organisations” which it believed may not have had a direct interest in the matter at hand (paragraph 24). This is about ten cases a year, representing about 0.08 per cent of claims filed in 2012. These figures do not represent a problem</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">even if one accepts the government’s judgement that the organisations involved did not have a direct interest</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">As the government acknowledges, these cases tend to be relatively successful. It is likely therefore that the organisations taking the cases are</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> seriously weighed their prospects of success and appear to be weighing them correctly.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">We do not believe that the Government should legislate to amend the test for standing. PCS is concerned that the amendments </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">put forward </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">are simply being proposed becau</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">se cases lodged by claimants who may not have had a direct interest in the matter at hand are relatively successful. Therefore this would potentially restrict access to redress unfair and unlawful decisions made by the state.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> government’s</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">amend the test for standing</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> also present us with an unfair</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> and confusing</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> two-tier system whereby there would be a </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">higher threshold to cross for non-environmental matters.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">We do not believe that sufficient evidence has</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> been presented to identify judi</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">cial reviews being used as campaigning tool as being </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">a problem. Rather than seeking to limit judicial review applications in this way, the Government should be seeking to identify the reasons there has been a rise in cases being brought forward. The cause </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">for the more than doubling in applications could be that the underlying problem is </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">the result of faults in the initial decisions which are being challenged.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS does no</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> support changing the rules on interveners. Interveners are only permitted to interven</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">e with the permission of the Court i.e. where the Court considers they have additional points to make material to the issues at hand. There are therefore already appropriate protections in place to prevent irrelevant interventions.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">Membership </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">organisations have legitimate interest in tak</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">ing forward proposals on behalf</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> of the people they represent.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">All members of our society have an interest in the proper administration of executive power and therefore access to judicial review should be not re</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">stricted to those directly affected by the matter at hand.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Procedural defects</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS believes that there has not been sufficient evidence presented to prove that the current test applied by the court is flawed. The proposal will not in any event achieve the G</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">overnment’s stated aim.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">In its consultation the Government asked whether the consideration of the “no difference” argument should be bought forward to permission</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">stage on the assertion of the defendant in the Acknowledgment of Service. We do not believe </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">that t</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">he proposal will not achieve the Government’s stated aim of preventing delay to “perfectly reasonable decisions or actions”. Where decisions or actions are “perfectly reasonable”, judicial review challenges will, in any event, be filtered out of the </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">system at the permission stage.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">Where cases involving challenges to unlawful decision making (which are the ones that will be caught by this proposal) are filtered out at the permission stage, decision makers will not receive guidance from the court to en</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">able them to avoid future unlawful decisions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Public Sector Equality Duty </span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS does not believe that there is a suitable alternative to judicial review for resolving disputes relating to the </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">Public Sector Equality Duty (</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PSED</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">he government has not </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">made a convincing case that reform is necessary. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">Any small likelihood of a dispute arising under the PSED, or becoming the subject of judicial review could be reduced firstly by giving public bodies more resources and support in meeting the PSED. The TUC</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> has made detailed recommendations in this </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">regard to the Independent Steering Group into the review of the PSED.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">The body with statutory duty to ensure compliance with PSED, the Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) should have appropriate powers </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">and resources to be able to address potential breaches at an early stage. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">PCS represents</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> around 280</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> members </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> EHRC</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">we </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">are concerned that</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> is woefully under resourced to perform this function. It has to monitor compliance with the PSED of an estim</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">ated 30,000 public bodies, but has only ever taken formal action in a small number of cases. In response to a recent Freedom of Information request, the EHRC replied that it had only used it</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> power to make an assessment relating to the PSE</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">D (s.31 Equality </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">Act 2006) on ten</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> occasions; and had only issued compliance notices relating to the equality duties to public bodies (s.32 Equality Act 2006) on six occasions, and none since the PSED came into effect under the 2010 Act.</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">The consultation document cites the</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> recent review of the PSED which claims that “it is not uncommon” for public bodies found to have failed to comply with the PSED “to arrive at the same conclusion following further work to demonstrate it had discharged the duty effectively”. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">However, the</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> evidence that exists would seem to undermine this claim. The Equality and Diversity Forum (EDF) have shown, in the six cases where the High Court granted an application for </span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">judicial review</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt"> only one of those resulted in the public body reaching the same de</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">cision. In the other five cases the public bodies made positive changes that would have otherwise most not likely not occurred. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">In the 13 years since the Race Relations (Amendment) Act of 2000, only 115 equality duty-related cases have been decided. A Re</span><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">port of the Independent Steering Group into the PSED concluded that cases brought under the PSED are still relatively rare, and “cases are seldom brought solely under the PSED”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> November 2013</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Segoe UI'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> TUC Response to the Review of the Public Sector Equality Duty, 19 April, available at: </span><a href="http://www.tuc.org.uk/sites/default/files/tucfiles/tucresponsepsedreview.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.tuc.org.uk/sites/default/files/tucfiles/tucresponsepsedreview.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Report of the Independent Steering Group into the Public Sector Equality Duty. Onli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ne at: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-independent-steering-groups-report-of-the-public-sector-equality-duty-psed-review-and-government-response"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-independent-steering-groups-report-o</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">f-the-public-sector-equality-duty-psed-review-and-government-response</span></a></p></body></html>